text: Perfect example of modern day fear porn propoganda. The Purge is clearly a trauma/fear based movie meant to dehumanize people and plant irrational thoughts of living without a powerful government. We are clearly In a time of perpetual manipulation and encroachment of abusive authoritarian powers and dwindling diversity in corporate ownership over key areas of societal influence, in particular, media outlets. Universal Pictures is owned by Comcast (GE, NBC, Universal, USA Network…) who is trying to merge with Time Warner cable (CNN, CW, HBO, Cartoon Network, TBS, TNT, AOL, DC Comics…) which means you'll be getting even less diversity in thought food where once there over 60 or so companies 10 years ago. This means that American media will be coming from only 5 large corporations soon. Does that comfort you? 5 corporate 'families'  giving you your cultural thought updates of what to laugh at, what to love, what to fear, what to wear, how to think? Do you believe a sane society would really want this type of garbage out during a time of world political upheaval and rapid change of technology and economy? No, this is all meant for your reaction so that you'll be thankful for the cameras everywhere and the police who are armed up like military soldiers on the streets. Better wise up fast because your mind does not have a firewall.

text: I was annoyed at the first Purge because they had an interesting idea but used it to just set up another "home invasion movie." So this looks like an improvement. But the whole idea of a yearly "Purge" is really flawed because even if this did somehow lead to low crime rates, the millions in damages couldn't offset the benefits.  Also by "all crime is legal" what does that entail? Sure people will run around stealing, raping, killing, etc. but does that mean scientists can perform illegal experiments on people or animals? Do stockbrokers start doing insider trading for that 12 hours?  Not to mention "cancelling all emergency services" could never work.  Home injuries, childbirth and heart attacks won't take a night off so are those folks, who stayed in their homes just screwed?

text: How would the "the purge" as put in this moviw would fail? Every armed citizen in the US not conformed with this would arm on the Purge day and patrol the streets killing criminals in the act. That is talking about policemen, armymen, military officers, NRA members, armed civilians, emergency personel, etc.   In a matter of hours, long before the Purge ends, the whole country would be razed by civil war. Depending on the intensity of the conflict, and how prepared each faction is, mayhem would only scalate becoming more and more destructive by the minute. In other words, cities will burn in flames. Roads would be rendered impassable. Important builds left unattended would lay in ruins.   By the end of the Purge, every mayor city in the country would rack up damages in the billions of dollars. With every important institution severely broken, even unable to recover, the economy would plummet to the ground. With all kinds of professionals, and other valuable workers lost in the Purge, the remaining industry would have serious problems recovering.  If the violence doesn't stop by dawn, the civil war will become uncontrollable, and threaten the very structure of the system.   Yeah, it pretty much sounds like a great idea.

So, in this scene, the audience is thinking "shit, they're fucked", but then in a twist, the guy in the god mask will jump out and save the day. Stuff like this happens in a lot of movies, where someone who seems bad, turns out to be good, at the end. And, I predict, they're going to do this with this character. Just a theory...

I'm talking someplace like Death Valley, or the mountains in Colorado, or something like that.  Once the purge was done, I would transfer everything back to my house and move back in.  Also, I would buy lots of metal bars to put on the windows of my house, and lots of bolts and blocks and stuff to keep the doors shut. text: Well really none of it makes sense. Let's say that the government decides to make crime legal for 12 hours of the year. Since I didn't see any evidence of people not being able to exit the country, then why wouldn't everyone just leave? I mean, honestly, even if you didn't have a passport, I am sure you could find a way to get out of the country, especially if your life depended on it. Then those who are left in the country, would be the people looking to "have fun" and those who couldn't get out (which to me would seem like a very small number). Therefore I really wouldn't see the point of committing ANY crimes. The majority of people would be gone, and if you were someone looking to have fun, you would have to deal with all of the other psychopaths out there looking for fun too. I mean, it seems to me like it would be smarter to commit crimes on days OTHER than the purge. I mean, the point of crime is surprise. No one is going to rob from a home, when the residents can shoot you down with no legal reason necessary. And the ones who are NOT looking to have fun, but still couldn't get out of the country, could easily just drive (or walk) to an isolated landscape and hide. I mean, it is only TWELVE HOURS. It isn't like they would be able to find you or even know of you if you hid well enough. Even places like NYC, if most of the country were gone, you could break into an office building, go to a random floor, and hide in a cabinet.

text: I think these movies are fundamentally illogical, and here's why:   Would the average person just start committing violent acts during the purge just because they knew they wouldn't be put in prison? I'm not some kind of humanist who thinks people are good deep down, but this still seems really unlikely to me. Suppose that 5% of the population were morally capable of committing violent crimes during the purge; if the other 95% were well-armed, the bad people would be severely outnumbered. In fact, we probably wouldn't even know which people were among that 5%, since they wouldn't be stupid enough to try anything anyway. And who's to say that neighborhoods and communities couldn't hire trusted cops (or soldiers, or MMA fighters, etc.) privately to provide them security during the purge hours?    But let's suppose that some people still ended up committing violent crimes during the purge. They wouldn't be put in prison, but does that mean that their behavior would have no repercussions? I think it's likely that private companies would emerge whose sole purpose would be to investigate violent acts committed during the purge, kind of like a private court system. Maybe they'd be composed of retired or active detectives, judges, etc. After reaching a "verdict," they would post the names of the people they found guilty on their website for all to see and would name the crimes committed. The "convicts" could then be economically ostracized. No one would hire them for a job; no apartment would rent to them; the electric, gas, water, and internet companies wouldn't provide them services; all the local stores would have their names and faces posted so the cashiers wouldn't serve them; etc. etc. And the businesses who did serve them would themselves face the ire of their customers.   Then maybe there would be other companies who would build apartment complexes specifically for these personas non grata, and would offer them a contractual arrangement whereby they would provide them food and shelter for x number of years, and in exchange, they could not leave the complex without permission and would do some kind of work for the companies who own the complex. It would be a prison system of sorts, but far more humane, and entirely voluntary (as it would certainly be preferable to starving to death in the streets).   By way of this purely non-coercive system of justice, you'd bypass the public court system entirely and would disincentivize violent behavior during the purge.

text: It's pretty good.  One guy looking for vengeance (because a drunk driver killed his son, and got off on a technicality) ends up with 4 survivors through the city.  They end up getting chased around by a couple of groups.  One is run by the government and is most equipped with 18 wheelers with mini-guns in the back and full swat type teams.  Another is a group with trucks and motorcycles which captures people and sells them to the rich that do their own "in-house" purge away for danger.  This last group caught the main 5 characters and sold them.  As they were hunted down by the highest bidders (7 of them), they killed 5 of the hunters.  The organizers got security to finish the hunt, but an anti-purge black panther type group busted in and saved the day.  One of the five main characters died in this battle.  After this, the guy looking for vengeance still went and tried to kill his target, but spared him.  After he left that house, one of the government hunter groups caught up to him and before a gunfight, but the purge time was over and he survived.

Other crimes like hacking into databses, rape, releasing bio-weapons, drug exchanges, etc would've been interesting too. If there is another sequel, I would like to see a person trying to leave the country the day before (cause that's what I would do) or seeing the Purge catch on in other countries.

text: You know, I'm not an uptight guy nor am I a guy with religious propensities (I'm agnostic) but, who the hell approves these kinds of films?? These things should not exist for the merely fair and simple reason that ANYONE can access them.. We live in a planet in which there are SICK people. I frown at the fact that we blame the misguided when we should really be blaming the people who actually didn't reject the making of this goddamn film (and its sequel) as well as those who aggrandize and perpetuate the "thrill" this incites. We should hold the person who created this accountable for whatever may or may not happen. As if these events would ever change anything! Once again, I am not religious but I certainly have a spiritual and emotional sense. Instead of producing borderline idiotic (if they haven't yet reached that point!), why don't we actually get in touch with what we are FEELING in lieu of the shit we're SEEING?

text: Do you understand how the economy works? Everybody wouldn't be rich, it would just be a restructuring of the classes. If poor and middle class people die, with the rich being left, then that would incentivise companies to increase prices, effectively creating a new middle class from the lower upper class. The only way to counter this would be to hyper-inflate America's economy, which is also a terrible idea. Also, with the middle and lower classes decimated, many industries would cease to exist (until a new middle class was formed from the bottom of the upper class) such as mining, agriculture, manufacturing, education, office work. This would destroy many of the rich peoples companies, as they have no workers. There would also be huge costs associated with the clean up after the purge. Imagine the costs and manpower required to clear cities and towns of millions of bodies, and repair billions of dollars worth of damaged infrastructure. The emergency services would also be completely overwhelmed. Hospitals would be flooded with victims (Ever seen a hospital in a war torn country? America would look like that), and many doctors and nurses would have died during the purge. Insurance costs would also sky rocket, and many insurance companies may even refuse to insure you for purge related incidents. What about people in hospitals too, for instance some one in intensive care? because I am pretty certain no medical staff would risk staying in a hospital as they are prime looting targets considering the millions of dollars worth of drugs and high-tech medical equipment. Government spending would have to increase to deal with the replacement of this, and to deal with all the people now on welfare because they became disabled during the purge, or now need counselling due to emotional trauma. Taxes would likely have to rise. What if a fire started during the purge? That could burn out of control for at most 12 hours, and by the time fire fighters are able to respond, the blaze could be out of control, lasting for days. Imagine what would happen if a fire blazed uninterrupted for 12 hours in New York city, it would costs billions of dollars, and kill and injure thousands.   Crime would also not go down, because most crime is not a one time incident, it is a habit and can be affected by factors such as economic status. Don't you think crime syndicates would take this opportunity to smuggle millions of illegal weapons into the country, and further maintain their grip on communities through terror killings or extortion. What about culturally significant buildings such as museums, landmarks, and art galleries? Would America's culture be allowed to vanish overnight? Other illegal activities would also be allowed to occur. Imagine the vast amount of drugs smuggled in from south of the border unimpeded. Other countries or groups could launch terrorist attacks without anyone stopping them. The purge would allow criminal groups to become larger, and more dangerous. Businesses, especially small businesses would be cripples, as they may lose huge amounts of resources, or staff. This would be terrible for the economy as these business now longer exist, therefore they don't pay taxes and the employees and employers must now receive welfare money. The American stock market would crash, as people would not want to invest in companies so liable of falling overnight. Large companies would also likely have to pay extremely high insurance costs. There would also be a huge amount of police inquiries needed. You don't think people would just suddenly stop the crime once the purge ends? It would continue for at least another 24 hours. What about people who were murdered just after the purge? It would take a huge amount of police resources to try and uncover whether the action occurred during purge time.   The Purge would be incredibly inhumane, and would destroy America's economy, and society.

text: I love reading fan fiction, where people add or change things in their favorite movie stories. I would love to see The Purge mixed in with other movie ideas, Purge Fan Fiction Crossovers. The first one I'd like to see is one dealing with The Expendables, where they are caught in the wake of a new experimental weapon, and are transported from Earth Prime to the world of The Purge. There, they have to survive, and defend as many innocents as they can, before they can find their way back to Earth Prime. The second idea would deal with Batman, where he is hit by an experimental weapon, but instead of dying he is transported to the world of The Purge, where he must defend the innocent, and discovers that the Bruce Wayne of Purge Earth is evil, and becomes Batman only for the night of The Purge, where he hunts the poor using his gadgets and fighting prowess, and the Bruce Wayne/Batman of Earth Prime must fight and stop him, Bruce Wayne must battle Bruce Wayne! The third idea would deal with Black Widow and Hawkeye, where they accidentally trigger a new Hydra device, and are transported to Purge Earth, where they discover that Hydra agents are there testing new weapons on people, all under the guise of being people who are Purging. The Black Widow and Hawkeye must stop them, and survive the other hunter teams out to kill them! The fourth idea would deal with Daredevil and The Punisher, where they are transported to Purge Earth, and must discover how they got there, and survive long enough to find their way home! And finally, I would like to see the crew of The Serenity, transported back to Earth That Was, and must find the parts to fix their crashed ship, and survive the night against hunter teams. But they have a weapon the hunter teams don't have: River Tam!

text: Damn, how much money are the filmakers getting from the Pentagon here? It really makes me feel as if we could NEVER EVER live without their (purely benevolent, competent, and unprejudiced) hand guiding my actions. I mean, it's almost genius, really; getting millions of people thinking that Anarchy means you can do whatever heinous, ornery thing to anyone you want. Ultimately it makes it easier to have them act in a way that justifies government/corporate control, when given the temporary illusion of being free. The actual MEANING of the term, and the underlying political philosophies behind it, just get overshadowed.   As a person who knows that true morality and human decency doesn't come at gunpoint, I think I'll pass.

text: The purge is the opposite of anarchy. A purge actually further seeks to legitimize and reinforce government as the purge itself is government authorized and the government is granted immunity from it. Why is the government protected from the purge? My theory is because the purge represents how government promotes division, disorder, and chaos among people in order to legitimize itself. Because when people are providing social order without government then government constitutes itself by creating disorder and conflict between people in order to monopolize social order. Unauthorized social order is punished with authorized disorder.

text: The whole premise of this movie is "natural selection". In nature, whether through disease, starvation, or predators, the weak are culled from the herd so that only the strong survive. Weakness is removed from the herd leaving it to be made up of the strong. Survival of the Fittest = Those who are fit/able to survive, do. Those who are unfit/unable to survive, do not.  In the case of "The Purge: Anarchy", weakness and strength are determined by wealth. The "strong" (ie: the wealthy) are able to survive due to being able to afford the means to do so. The "weak" (ie: the poor) cannot afford the means to insure their own survival and thus they do not survive. As a result, their numbers are thinned and a reduction in the population of the "weak" (ie: the poor) results in a reduction of crime and unemployment... thus, a healthier "herd" (ie: society).
